bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: John Henry Lefroy, soldier, scientist, and surveyor, was born in the village of Ashe, Hampshire, England on January 28, 1817. After attending private schools in Alton and Richmond he was entered as an officer-cadet in the Royal Military Academy at Woolwich in January of 1831. In December of 1834 he was gazetted second lieutenant in the Royal Artillery and in 1837 promoted to lieutenant and posted to Chatham.

In the spring of 1839, acting on a proposal which had been made by Alexander Von Humboldt three years earlier, the British Government decided to establish a number of magnetic observatories throughout the British Empire. In conjunction with this, a number of specially selected officers were sent to Dublin to receive instructions in the use of scientific instruments under Professor Humphrey Lloyd of Trinity College. Among them was Lieutenant J. H. Lefroy.

After several weeks of training in Dublin, he was sent to the island of St. Helena for further experience where he remained until July of 1842 when he was sent to take charge of the observatory which had been recently opened in Toronto, Canada West. In April of 1843, Lefroy, with a number of assistants and voyageurs, set out on a magnetic surveying expedition into the Northwest territories of Canada which lasted until November of 1844, and established, among other things, an approximate position of the magnetic North Pole.

In 1853, Lefroy, by then a Captain, was recalled to England, where he continued his military duties and scientific interests. From 1871 to 1877 he served as Governor and Commander-in-Chief of the Bermudas; and from 1880 to 1882 as Governor of Tasmania. John Henry Lefroy died on April 11, 1890 in Cornwall, England. For additional information regarding Lefroy, see George F. G. Stanley, editor, John Henry Lefroy In Search of the Magnetic North - A Soldier-Surveyor's Letters from the North-West 1843-1844 (Toronto, 1955).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The journals represent, as near as it is possible to tell, all of the manuscript volumes that Lefroy kept as a daily account of both his scientific readings and his personal observations while on the magnetic surveying expedition mentioned above. These volumes were believed to have been lost in 1846 (cf. Stanley, page i and the frontispiece to page 1) but in 1972 they were discovered in the Loomis-Wilder Famiily Papers (MS 496A) in the Yale University Library.

Volume 1 ("Journal 1843") covers the period May 1 to September 23, 1843 and contains daily magnetic readings taken by Lefroy and members of the expedition. In addition, for each daily entry there are personal comments describing the weather, the geology, flora and fauna of the region, various events in the course of the expedition, and comments on Indian tribes encountered. Volume 2 ("Journal 1844") covering the period March 26 to November 18, 1844 is of a slightly different format, containing less and more informally recorded scientific information. There is, however, a consequently greater proportion of detailed personal observations which in this volume are interspersed with sketches made by Lefroy of various geologic phenomena, plants, tools, and Indians.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The diary documents Bruss's work and family life in the Soviet Union during the 1930s and 1940s; the Soviet home front during World War II; women in the Soviet Union; denunciation in the Soviet Union, and her family's experiences during the Russian civil war and collectivization. Included is a typewritten version of the diary and a newspaper account documenting the discovery of the diary, both in Russian.
